		Comment <a href="#c_1713662132">7</a> by Ken Dunnington
		posted on 2/8/2007 at 9:11 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>Echoing the sentiments above, I think learning the core, as well as the syntax is a much better approach than diving into the advanced topics. And I think we all can agree that making mistakes is one of the best ways to become a better programmer. "Advanced" techniques don't mean much if you don't know *why* you would use them; i.e. it's very difficult to see why you'd want to use a framework until you develop a site with a ton of page controllers and spaghetti code. I don't think any book, website or mailing list can give you that "a-ha!" moment you need to really "get" some of the more advanced topics like experience can (though it can't hurt!)</p><p>Learning multiple languages is a great way to shorten the gap between picking up the syntax and language basics, and being ready to tackle the more advanced aspects of the language. In fact, once you learn advanced techniques in one language, it's often much, much easier to apply those to another language once you learn the basics.</p></div>
