		Comment <a href="#c_1713662135">9</a> by Rob Brooks-Bilson
		posted on 2/8/2007 at 10:02 PM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I think it's also a matter of background.  For example, I just got back from Taiwan, where a co-worker and I spent two weeks teaching ColdFusion to a team of .Net developers.  We had a specif goal - for them to develop an application in mach-ii that would fit in our customer portal.</p><p>Since they all had programming backgrounds, we didn't have to spend time teaching basic programming concepts.  We were able to focus on the ColdFusion basics - setting variables, writing queries, passing around parameters, http get and post, data structures, and then move on to components.</p><p>We didn't teach much about mach-ii other than the basic.  The point is that once you know one language, learning another language is often just a matter of syntax, and knowing what's available to make doing a particular task easier.  In our case, we taught them enough CF to get going, and through code reviews, are helping them to learn faster ways to do things using ColdFusion's awesome array of tags and functions.</p><p>Note that we did not explicitly teach them about ColdFusion's security framework, as our customer portal handles the majority of security for the app.  We did teach cfqueryparam and data type checking and exception and error handling, though.</p><p>So far, after having taught several groups using this approach, we've found that it works reasonably well for our needs.</p><p>As with anything, though, the more time you have, the better.  Also, there's no better teacher than experience, and no better way to gain experience than by doing.</p></div>
	</div>
</div>
		
