		<div class="comment_text"><p>Hi Steve,</p><p>We always include CFCs in our training, since all of our applications are written using them.</p><p>For some training we did last year with developers in the Philippines, where the programmers had little development experience, we started off with the Fast Track to CF class (delivered remotely using RoundPeg).  After that class, Adam Crump and I went to the Philippines and followed up (about 2 weeks later) with more training, but this time focused exclusively on CFEclipse, CVS, and CFC based development.</p><p>What's interesting is that we use Mach-II, and are able to get developers working within the framework without really understanding all of the ins and outs of the framework.  This only works on certain types of applications, and mainly because the apps are being built to fit in an already existing portal that has a lot of services already built.</p><p>But to answer your question, I do think that CFCs can be taught as part of the basics.  CFCs themselves are pretty simple to learn - it's their application that can take a lot more time, practice, and experience to master.  I'm reminded of Ray's example of the "uber-CFC" vs how a CFC would be used in a fully OO MVC style environment.</p></div>
