		Comment <a href="#c_1713662117">20</a> by doug
		posted on 2/9/2007 at 2:27 AM
		</div>
		<div class="comment_text"><p>I am a couple of years into ColdFusion now and started out with just the simple basic templates with some forms, queries, and other elements which are used in just about every site I develop.  As a matter of fact, CF is my first language (I think that individuals with experience in other languages certainly have an advantage when adopting new languages, including CF.  For instance, concepts in JS and AS have made much more sense to me having been working with CF.).  I, like many, used CFWACK as my primary introduction to learning CF.  What I have come to realize is that when I begin to separate what is a web site from what is a web application I find that more advanced topics need be learned in order to accommodate an application's requirements.  So I look at problems of an "advanced" nature from an application specific point of view.  This for me translates into the more applications I work on, the more CF I learn.  At the same time it becomes easy to recognize how reusable CF is from application to application.  Certainly I want to become better at what I am doing with CF but it is not realistic to think that you can know everything about CF.  I think CF, as with any programming language, is a continuing study that one will learn something new regardless of how long one has been writing CF.  Plus it would get boring if you new it all - don't you think?</p></div>
